When I started building this account, I learned quickly that shedding skin would earn me likes and followers. I took it because I’ve always been comfortable in my sensuality, I wasn’t raised to hide that side of myself. It isn’t what defines me, but it can often be a source of strength. I did because I ENJOYED it. I wanted to give myself permission to be seen, I wanted every post to be a love letter to my body, an expression of art! But, it didn’t really work out that way…

I gave more than I’d hoped. It catches up when you’re boundaries are crossed. I can’t take it back but I learned my limits. I’ll admit, I’m fearful and untrusting of the dark parts of admiration. I question intentions, I block out any unsolicited opinions about my body. And yes, I can recognize that I reaped the benefits, but I paid for with my peace. I had to reclaim that source of strength that my sensuality once gave me. It’s been a process.

Now I’m no longer bracing myself every time I post a swimsuit or lingerie picture. I’m no longer reading forums of admirers hoping I’ll gain weight for their own satisfaction. I’m focused on my expression and going back to my creative roots, posting what feels like me. And definitely what you guys wanna see, of course. 

Sometimes I wanna be edgy, fierce, sexy. Sometimes I wanna drown in rainbows and put colorful clips in my hair. BOTH are me, that doesn’t make me a freak or a child. But I know that of myself, and it’s ok if you want to make assumptions. 

I love me enough to take it because this form of expression gives me freedom. I’m not giving it up like I once thought I would. 

Every once in awhile, I look through crowd to see the real ones cheering me on. My besties, my cheerleaders, my ride-or-dies..y’all make it all worth it. I’m here because of you 🫶🏽 thank you from the bottom of my heart ♥️

Something about Yellow 🌻💛 @fashionnovacurve ⬇️

Happy Summer everyone! ☀️ Florida is endless summer but it never seems to be any less magical of a time for me. 

And you know why? I’ve discovered people are so insecure of their own bodies that they’re not even paying attention to my rolls in swimsuit at the beach. And on the rare occasion someone makes a rude face, I just hope it helps them to see me happy. 

If being fat is the worst that someone could imagine, I know they’re thinking, “how was she smiling?”

Being body positive isn’t ignoring all the challenges that come with living in a larger body, societal and physical. It’s loving the journey, acknowledging that your body has brought you were you are now.

In that moment, my body aids me to enjoy the crash of the waves, the salt in the air, and freedom to smile 🙏🏼💛

Sometimes I don’t suck in and my belly rolls peek out.

Sometimes the cellulite on my bum doesn’t help me feel “bootylicious.”

Sometimes I don’t get the shot I want and later wish I posed differently.

More than I care to admit, I look in the mirror and will find something I don’t like…

But what doesn’t change is the joy I feel knowing I’m on one of the most beautiful beaches in the world, with my friends, making memories I’ll remember forever.

Go live. You get one life, one body babe. I promise you, that smile is outshines every insecurity 🫶🏽☀️
